		<tr>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=3>
				The Forges of Innoruuk <br>  <br> A lay sermon by Rakash Tzg`Nash <br>  <br> An indigo rogue began her work at one of several forges in Neriak.  Her tools of the trade at hand, raw ore for smelting, her hammer, an anvil, molds and buckets for cooling water.  <br>  <br> As her hands loaded in the coal her foot began pumping the bellow to coax the fires to life.  This night was a night of hard work, sweat and reverence in service to her Father and her people.   <br>  <br> &quot;Ah, the coals begin to burn and give their fuel for my work.&quot;  She began to equate her work upon the forge to the work of Innoruuk within His children.  &quot;It is a wonder to think upon a higher calling in all we dark elves do.  We go about our daily tasks and should think upon them as holy service and worship for Our Father.&quot; <br>  <br> When the forge reached the correct temperature she placed the ore within it to begin the refining process.  &quot;The raw ore is as a child, newly born to be nurtured in the warm embrace of Innoruuk's hate for all who would oppose Him.  We must refine the valuable metal in the ore from the waste.  Purity is key, impurities would render the metal useless and breakable.  We must be pure of heart in our service to Our Father, He will not abide a weak blade in His service.&quot; <br>  <br> Once the indigo rogue was left with refined ore she began the task of consolidating the smaller pieces into a larger workable sheet with a great amount of reheating, hammering, and folding upon the anvil.  &quot;As I work this metal into something useable, Our Father likewise works his children into material for His service.  Through constant adversity we are worked into a people who rely on each other for solidarity and survival.  We learn that to be unbendable and unbreakable we must think alike in our faith and end goal.&quot; <br>  <br> The rogue worked the metal sheet, heating, hammering and folding it a prescribed number of times to get it perfect for the next step in the process.  She placed the metal sheet into a heated mold and let the heat of the forge do its work as the sheet almost magically melted into the contours of the mold.  &quot;As this metal fits into the contours of this mold our children fit into our society in service to Our Father.  As this mold determines the armor or weapon that I make Innoruuk determines the path of His children.  I may make gorgets or boots, Our Father may make clerics or warriors.  All find their place within His molding of us.&quot; <br>  <br> When the metal had conformed to the mold the indigo rogue then submerged it into a bucket of water to cool it just enough to remove a still steaming rough piece of armor.  &quot;As this piece of armor had been submerged and tempered so are Innoruuk's servants baptized into His service.  Our baptism is one of blood instead of water, of our first battle in service to our race and our god.  We are still very rough at this time and need further refinement.  As I take a file to this metal to round the rough spots Our Father in His Will refines and shapes our people in each battle and quest.&quot; <br>  <br> The tiny rogue worked the metal with a file, knocking off any rough edges and smoothing the metal by a little more heating, hammering and tempering in water.  When the piece is nearly complete she stops to admire it and think more upon Innoruuk's working of her race. <br>  <br> &quot;As this armor is now tempered within the fire of the forge so are our people tempered and strengthened in Innoruuk's hatred.  We shall not bend and we shall not break for we are strong and stand united in defense of our homeland and people.  As I have unmade impure ore into pure metal so does Innoruuk unmake the lightdweller's world into purified dark elf land.  The very earth gives up it's dead into service for Our Father.  We shall be strong and unyielding as fine steel in Our Father's hate.&quot; <br>  <br> Her work at the forge being done for the day the tiny indigo rogue blacksmith packs up her gear until next time and takes her finished armor pieces for wear by her race and allies.  She stops on her way by the Church of Innoruuk and gives an offering and praise for her role in dark elf society.  &quot;May I serve You and our people well, Great Father of the Teir'Dal.&quot; <br>  <br> &quot;Lightdwellers fear the glory of Innoruuk, for we shall unmake your world.&quot; <br>  <br> Amen.		

